{"ts":"2026-06-27T13:26:01.911Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Reviewing Current APIs**\n\nI'm impressed by the simple yet powerful node APIs and the test dashboard's role in their validation. My immediate task involves designing GET endpoints for `/api/v1/analytics/client` and `/api/v1/analytics/admin`. I need to re-examine the specifications to proceed effectively.\n\n\n**Defining Data Aggregates**\n\nI'm now zeroing in on defining the precise properties to be returned by each aggregate. I'm focusing on \"counts by status\", \"counts by phase\", \"support by priority\", \"invoice by status\", \"AI operations by health\", and \"governance by severity\", confirming I can group each logically. This should simplify the data structures. I've eliminated the possibility of fake or live analytics.\n\n\n**Structuring Data Aggregates**\n\nI'm now determining how best to structure the data aggregation. Instead of individually defining all those aggregate properties, I'm thinking of creating a generic aggregator function or utilizing standard JavaScript loops and reducers directly in the route handlers. This seems more efficient, and I also need to account for client roles and their respective data access limitations, meaning I need to filter data.\n\n\n**Analyzing Authentication Methods**\n\nI am now thoroughly examining the authentication methods, focusing on how `getAuthCaller(req)` is implemented and the helper libraries utilized, especially in `/api/v1/analytics/client`. I've found an import path issue to `lib/api-auth`, which needs correction. I also need to assess the client and admin role data access implications. My analysis aims to unify the routes or keep them distinct.\n\n\n**Verifying Import Paths**\n\nI'm now confirming the correct number of directory traversals needed for imports. Tracing up from `app/api/v1/analytics/client/route.ts` and `app/api/v1/analytics/admin/route.ts` confirms that the path `../../../../../lib/api-auth` is accurate. This also holds true for the authentication import path from `dashboard/admin/route.ts`. I will now review the database structures.\n\n\n**Extracting Mock Data**\n\nI'm now focusing on extracting data properties from mock objects. I need to get the status, phase, priority, and health. I am also checking the types of the object values like `ApiProject` and `ApiAiOperation` to identify the correct properties.\n\n\n**Clarifying Category Data**\n\nNow, I'm carefully analyzing the statuses within the data categories. I'm expanding on my previous work, and I realize I can calculate \"counts by status\" for each. This includes projects, support, invoices, AI operations, governance, and documents. This unified approach provides comprehensive data coverage and satisfies all requirements. I'm focusing on a clean aggregation structure.\n\n\n**Defining JSON Structure**\n\nI am now structuring the JSON format for the `/api/v1/analytics/admin` endpoint. I'm focusing on \"projects\", \"aiOperations\", \"documents\", and \"invoices\" objects with keys: \"totalCount\", \"byStatus\", and in some cases, \"byPhase\" or \"byHealth\". I aim for clarity and completeness in the returned `summary` object. The structure will be straightforward and easily parsed.\n\n\n**Refining Object Aggregations**\n\nI'm checking the attributes and values in the mock databases to normalize key casing. Dynamic map construction to handle varying values, like `item.status` or `item.severity`, is the plan to ensure flexibility. I'll iterate through items, incrementing counts for status, severity, and others dynamically.\n\nI can make it more explicit if I check the attributes and their values in the mock objects, such as `status`, `severity`, or others.\n\n\n**Implementing Dynamic Aggregation**\n\nI've crafted a dynamic aggregation approach using loops and objects. It gracefully handles new or custom statuses and phases, ensuring resilience. This adaptable method removes the need to hardcode all possible values. Now, I'm adapting this for all entities and will focus on its use in the client route.\n\n\n**Filtering Client Data**\n\nI'm now focusing on implementing the client-side data filtering. When a client member calls `/api/v1/analytics/client`, I need to ensure all entities are filtered by `callerClientId`. I'm tracing the code to verify that `clientProjects` and `clientOps` are properly filtered, verifying that the appropriate client's data is shown. I'm verifying the current implementation handles data access correctly.\n\n\n**Confirming Client Filters**\n\nI'm now carefully verifying the client-side data filtering implementation. I've re-examined the code and confirmed that `ApiGovernanceItem`, `ApiSupportTicket`, `ApiInvoice`, `ApiDocumentItem`, and `ApiAiOperation` all possess the required `client_id` property, ensuring proper data filtering for client-specific requests.\n\n\n**Verifying Filtering Scope**\n\nI'm now confirming the backend's checks, particularly focusing on authorization, as I noticed I need to handle token checks correctly. Specifically, I'm checking `getAuthCaller(req)` from `app/api/v1/dashboard/admin/route.ts` and `/client/route.ts` to ensure robust authorization for both roles.\n\n\n**Validating Authorization Logic**\n\nI'm now satisfied with the backend checks. The `getAuthCaller(req)` function now seems robust. The error codes cover missing headers, invalid tokens, non-existent users, and inactive accounts, matching the needs for the admin endpoint, and I've verified that admin access is global. Now I will focus on GET `/api/v1/analytics/client`.\n\n\n**Clarifying Admin Access**\n\nI'm now clarifying the access rules. I'm focusing on GET `/api/v1/analytics/admin`. It should return a global aggregate of all data, accessible *only* by the `gff_admin` role. Client roles will get a `403 Forbidden` error. I'm ensuring this aligns with the requirement that \"Admin roles see all\". I'll keep the client-specific data access for the client route.\n\n\n**Defining Design Plan**\n\nI'm now writing down the Design Plan clearly, as required. The goal is a secure and performant endpoint for client and admin analytics. This API will aggregate all GFF AI core entities from our mock databases. It's crucial for the data to represent a single source of truth across all GFF AI core entities (projects, AI operations, documents, invoices, support tickets, governance items). I'm focusing on projects to be grouped by status and phase.\n\n\n\n**Finalizing Entity Grouping**\n\nI'm now implementing the grouping logic for all entities to ensure proper data categorization. AI Operations are categorized by status and health. Documents, invoices, support tickets, and governance items are also categorized according to their respective requirements. I'm ensuring consistency in categorization across all entities and focusing on a consistent data structure.\n\n\n\n**Constructing Admin Route**\n\nI'm now carefully crafting the `app/api/v1/analytics/admin/route.ts` code, starting with correct imports of `lib/api-auth` and mock variables, including all mock database entities. The editor will auto-create the directory. Next, I will test for admin correctness and safety. I will write a dedicated automated test script to do this.\n\n\n**Confirming Module Exports**\n\nI'm now confirming the export of key functions and mock data from `lib/api-auth.ts`. I've verified the presence of `verifyJwt`, `API_MOCK_USERS`, and the mock data constants (projects, AI operations, invoices, etc.). All necessary exports are available. I am now proceeding with the development of the admin route, planning the GET request logic.\n\n\\n\\n\n**Developing Admin Logic**\n\nI am now beginning to code the logic for the GET request within `app/api/v1/analytics/admin/route.ts`. I am focusing on the admin route by importing required modules and mock data. I'm verifying the structure is as I expect. I'm building out the admin GET request.\n\n\n**Verifying Admin Authorization**\n\nI'm now carefully implementing the admin endpoint's authorization using `getAuthCaller(req)`. I've integrated this function to check the request's authorization header and user role to ensure only `gff_admin` users have access. The `try...catch` block wraps the code to manage potential errors gracefully. I'm focusing on providing clear error messages for unauthorized access, particularly with the 403 Forbidden status.\n\n\n**Implementing Entity Aggregation**\n\nI'm now implementing aggregation logic for each entity within the admin route, specifically inside `app/api/v1/analytics/admin/route.ts`. The implementation includes aggregating projects by status and phase and also aggregating AI operations by status and health. This comprehensive approach is being expanded to all entities to ensure complete data coverage and consistent structure across the admin data. I'm focusing on the modularity of the aggregation logic.\n\n\n**Refining Aggregation Logic**\n\nI'm now refining the aggregation of each entity, including projects, operations, documents, invoices, and support. I've built distinct aggregation logic for each item: projects (status, phase), operations (status, health), documents (status), invoices (status), and support tickets (status, priority). I am ensuring the structure is modular and adaptable.\n\n\n**Finalizing Admin Response**\n\nI'm now putting the finishing touches on the response structure for the admin endpoint. I've aggregated all the data, and included projects, AI operations, and now documents, using a modular and adaptable approach. I've added governance tickets. I am now focusing on the final format to ensure comprehensive data is included and returned consistently to the admin.\n\n\n**Designing Client Route**\n\nI'm now designing the `app/api/v1/analytics/client/route.ts` using the same structure, but ensuring the data is properly filtered by the client's ID. I'm focusing on ensuring RBAC works, and that it mirrors the admin route for modularity, and that it provides the correct, filtered data. This includes projects, AI operations, documents, invoices, support, and governance.\n\n\n\n**Implementing Client Logic**\n\nI'm now implementing the GET request logic within `app/api/v1/analytics/client/route.ts`, ensuring data filtering by the client ID for proper access. I'm verifying the structure is as expected and implementing the same data aggregation strategy as the admin route. I'm focused on the modularity of the aggregation logic and client access.\n\n\n**Refining Access Control**\n\nI am now focusing on refining the access control logic within both the admin and client routes. I'm carefully reviewing the code to handle various scenarios, including admin-requested client data and ensuring strict client-specific data filtering. I'm making sure that only the correct data is visible. I'm focusing on securing the API.\n\n\n**Confirming Client Filtering**\n\nI've implemented client-side data filtering for projects, documents, invoices, support, AI operations, and governance items within the client route. I've re-examined the code, confirming that only the relevant client's data is returned using `filter` on mock objects like `ApiAiOperation` and `ApiGovernanceItem`. This is the core work, and I need to test that it works.\n\n\n**Expanding Aggregation Methods**\n\nI am now expanding on data aggregation, having implemented individual loops and objects to aggregate statuses and health.  I've added documents, invoices, and support tickets to the method. The previous method did not include documents, invoices, support, and now governance items. I am now unifying and finalizing the aggregation.\n\n\n**Finalizing Response Object**\n\nI'm now completing the construction of the response object for both client and admin routes. I am including support and governance ticket aggregations, adding supportByStatus, supportByPriority, governanceByStatus, and governanceBySeverity. I'm ensuring all data, like AI operations and documents, is consistently structured within the summary object.\n\n\n"}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T13:26:01.914Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"tool","toolName":"editor","toolCallId":"nq5emv1h","input":{"path":"/Users/ayushbansal/Documents/GitHub/hirezapp_landing_page/app/api/v1/analytics/admin/route.ts","new_text":"import { NextResponse } from \"next/server\";\nimport { \n  API_MOCK_USERS, \n  API_MOCK_PROJECTS, \n  API_MOCK_AI_OPERATIONS,\n  API_MOCK_INVOICES,\n  API_MOCK_GOVERNANCE,\n  API_MOCK_DOCUMENTS,\n  API_MOCK_SUPPORT_TICKETS,\n  verifyJwt, \n  MockUserDbEntry,\n  ApiProject,\n  ApiAiOperation,\n  ApiDocumentItem,\n  ApiInvoice,\n  ApiSupportTicket,\n  ApiGovernanceItem\n} from \"../../../../../lib/api-auth\";\n\nexport const runtime = \"nodejs\";\n\nfunction getAuthCaller(req: Request) {\n  const auth = req.headers.get(\"authorization\");\n  if (!auth?.startsWith(\"Bearer \")) {\n    return { status: 401, error: \"Unauthorized\", msg: \"Missing/malformed Authorization header.\" };\n  }\n  const decoded = verifyJwt(auth.substring(7));\n  if (!decoded?.email) {\n    return { status: 401, error: \"Unauthorized\", msg: \"Invalid/expired access token.\" };\n  }\n  const user = (API_MOCK_USERS as Record<string, MockUserDbEntry>)[decoded.email.toLowerCase().trim()];\n  if (!user) {\n    return { status: 401, error: \"Unauthorized\", msg: \"Authorized user not found.\" };\n  }\n  if (user.status === \"inactive\") {\n    return { status: 403, error: \"Forbidden\", msg: \"This account is inactive.\" };\n  }\n  return { caller: user };\n}\n\nexport async function GET(req: Request) {\n  try {\n    const auth = getAuthCaller(req);\n    if (\"status\" in auth) {\n      return NextResponse.json({ success: false, error: auth.error, message: auth.msg }, { status: auth.status });\n    }\n    const { caller } = auth;\n\n    if (caller.role !== \"gff_admin\") {\n      return NextResponse.json(\n        { success: false, error: \"Forbidden\", message: \"Access denied. Only system administrators can fetch the global analytics summary.\" },\n        { status: 403 }\n      );\n    }\n\n    const projects = Object.values(API_MOCK_PROJECTS) as ApiProject[];\n    const operations = Object.values(API_MOCK_AI_OPERATIONS) as ApiAiOperation[];\n    const documents = Object.values(API_MOCK_DOCUMENTS) as ApiDocumentItem[];\n    const invoices = Object.values(API_MOCK_INVOICES) as ApiInvoice[];\n    const supportTickets = Object.values(API_MOCK_SUPPORT_TICKETS) as ApiSupportTicket[];\n    const governance = Object.values(API_MOCK_GOVERNANCE) as ApiGovernanceItem[];\n\n    // Aggregate Projects\n    const projectsByStatus: Record<string, number> = {};\n    const projectsByPhase: Record<string, number> = {};\n    projects.forEach(p => {\n      const status = p.status || \"unknown\";\n      projectsByStatus[status] = (projectsByStatus[status] || 0) + 1;\n      const phase = p.phase || \"unknown\";\n      projectsByPhase[phase] = (projectsByPhase[phase] || 0) + 1;\n    });\n\n    // Aggregate AI Operations\n    const operationsByStatus: Record<string, number> = {};\n    const operationsByHealth: Record<string, number> = {};\n    operations.forEach(o => {\n      const status = o.status || \"unknown\";\n      operationsByStatus[status] = (operationsByStatus[status] || 0) + 1;\n      const health = o.health || \"unknown\";\n      operationsByHealth[health] = (operationsByHealth[health] || 0) + 1;\n    });\n\n    // Aggregate Documents\n    const documentsByStatus: Record<string, number> = {};\n    documents.forEach(d => {\n      const status = d.status || \"unknown\";\n      documentsByStatus[status] = (documentsByStatus[status] || 0) + 1;\n    });\n\n    // Aggregate Invoices\n    const invoicesByStatus: Record<string, number> = {};\n    invoices.forEach(i => {\n      const status = i.status || \"unknown\";\n      invoicesByStatus[status] = (invoicesByStatus[status] || 0) + 1;\n    });\n\n    // Aggregate Support Tickets\n    const supportByStatus: Record<string, number> = {};\n    const supportByPriority: Record<string, number> = {};\n    supportTickets.forEach(t => {\n      const status = t.status || \"unknown\";\n      supportByStatus[status] = (supportByStatus[status] || 0) + 1;\n      const priority = t.priority || \"unknown\";\n      supportByPriority[priority] = (supportByPriority[priority] || 0) + 1;\n    });\n\n    // Aggregate Governance\n    const governanceByStatus: Record<string, number> = {};\n    const governanceBySeverity: Record<string, number> = {};\n    governance.forEach(g => {\n      const status = g.status || \"unknown\";\n      governanceByStatus[status] = (governanceByStatus[status] || 0) + 1;\n      const severity = g.severity || \"unknown\";\n      governanceBySeverity[severity] = (governanceBySeverity[severity] || 0) + 1;\n    });\n\n    return NextResponse.json({\n      success: true,\n      summary: {\n        projects: {\n          totalCount: projects.length,\n          byStatus: projectsByStatus,\n          byPhase: projectsByPhase\n        },\n        aiOperations: {\n          totalCount: operations.length,\n          byStatus: operationsByStatus,\n          byHealth: operationsByHealth\n        },\n        documents: {\n          totalCount: documents.length,\n          byStatus: documentsByStatus\n        },\n        invoices: {\n          totalCount: invoices.length,\n          byStatus: invoicesByStatus\n        },\n        support: {\n          totalCount: supportTickets.length,\n          byStatus: supportByStatus,\n          byPriority: supportByPriority\n        },\n        governance: {\n          totalCount: governance.length,\n          byStatus: governanceByStatus,\n          bySeverity: governanceBySeverity\n        }\n      }\n    });\n  } catch (err) {\n    return NextResponse.json({ success: false, error: \"Internal Server Error\" }, { status: 500 });\n  }\n}\n"}}}
